{"Body":"<p>As shown in the Wiktionary:</p>\n\n<p><em><strong><a href=\"http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/frigus#Latin\" rel=\"nofollow\">frigus</a></em></strong></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>From Proto-Indo-European *sriges-, *sriHges-.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>But I can't find the clue to this sound change on <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indo-European_sound_laws\" rel=\"nofollow\"><em>Wikipedia</em></a>, which concludes that PIE*bʰ, *dʰ, *gʷʰ will become L. f-, when they are <strong>\"At the beginning of a word\"</strong>.</p>\n", "Id":"3610", "Title":"How does PIE *s- in *sriges- change to L. f- in frigus?", "CreationDate":"2013-04-25T13:51:26.930", "AnswerCount":"2", "PostTypeId":"1", "OwnerUserId":"1306", "Tags":"<proto-indo-european><sound-change>", "comments":[], "ViewCount":"111", "LastActivityDate":"2013-04-27T00:19:20.817", "Score":"2", "CommentCount":"1", "OwnerUser":{"UpVotes":"13", "WebsiteUrl":"", "DownVotes":"0", "Id":"1306", "AccountId":"1783961", "Views":"2", "Reputation":"515", "CreationDate":"2012-09-03T14:12:48.473", "DisplayName":"archenoo", "LastAccessDate":"2014-01-16T14:31:46.963", "AboutMe":"<p>A linguistic amateur</p>\n", "Age":"25"}}